  "doc_id": "95",
  "text": "Whereas much has been learned about numerosity coding by neurons in the fronto-parietal cortex, the role of behavioral relevance and learning in the modulation of neuronal selectivity remains unexplored. Both parietal and PFC neurons show increased responses to behaviorally relevant as opposed to irrelevant stimuli [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Experience-dependent plasticity is further suggested by observations that visual neurons in prefrontal [CITATION_3] and parietal [CITATION_4] visual areas can respond highly selectively to familiar and well-trained visual stimuli. Not only do response properties change, but also the proportion and location of selective neurons change with learning [CITATION_5] . Moreover, prefrontal and posterior parietal neurons robustly reflect the learned category membership of visual stimuli, and visual selectivity shifts after monkeys were retrained to group the same stimuli into two new categories [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Whether abstract representations of quantity experience modifications with behavioral relevance, learning, and familiarity, however, remains elusive.",
